  "articleSummary": "This analytical article argues that prompt injection is the modern equivalent of SQL injection, occurring because LLMs cannot fundamentally distinguish between developer instructions and user-provided data. The author uses a historical framing device, comparing 2007-era web vulnerabilities to current agentic AI risks, where injected \"tokens\" can hijack tools, exfiltrate data, or escalate privileges. Intended for AI developers and architects, the piece maintains a cautionary yet practical tone, dismissing \"better prompting\" as a primary solution. Instead, it advocates for a multi-layered defense strategy involving input validation, dedicated classifier models (e.g., GPT-4o-mini), and the principle of least privilege for agent tools.",
